Course.Title: PRINCIPLES OF ACCOUNTING II
Course.Description: Principles of Accounting II is a continuation of the topics covered in Principles of Accounting I.  It builds on the skills, tools and techniques developed and utilized for measuring and analyzing a company's operating and financing activities.  The analysis and measuring analyzing a company's operating and financing activities.  The analysis and interpretation of financial statements will be emphasized.  Accounting for partnerships and corporations' equities will be included.  Special issues in connection with the accounting for investments and liabilities and the usefulness of the statement of cash flows will be addressed.  This course will focus on some of the tools and techniques used in managerial accounting.

Course.Title: INTERMEDIATE ACCT II

Course.Title: FEDERAL INCOME TAXES II
Course.Description: This course is the continuation of Federal Income Taxes I (ACCT 3230) and will cover: computing federal income taxes and determining and utilizing allowable credits, computing the overall tax result for a sole proprietorship business, determining the Alternative Minimum Tax for individuals, discussing and computing the various tax options related to property including the computation of the adjusted cost bases and resulting gains and losses at the time of sale or other disposition and optional are required tax treatment for specific tax events such as the sale of a primary residence, involuntary conversions, etc, basis rules regarding property received by gift or inheritance, special rules related to home ownership, basic issues related to tax free incorporation of an entity, and the basic understanding and some unique issues (which are different from individual tax issues) regarding corporations.

Course.Title: AUDITING FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
Course.Description: One out of the four sections of the Certified Public Accountant (CPA) exam is devoted exclusively to auditing, a required skill for the accounting profession. This course will identify the conceptual tools needed to find, organize, and evaluate evidence about the assertions of a third party through the practical application of auditing techniques. The connection between Auditing activities and the reliability of business accounting statements, together with related disclosures, are linked in this course to prior business and accounting courses. This course will also integrate the current regulatory environment and the Accounting Standards Board's (ASB) guidance when conducting an audit in accordance with Generally Accepted Auditing Standards (GAAS).
